ar exudates on microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely responsible for these histological findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cytomegalovirus","Influenza A virus","Measles virus","Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Pneumocystis jirovecii"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe characteristic histological finding in \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E pneumonia is a foamy or \u0027bubble-like\u0027 alveolar exudate. This appearance is created by the accumulation of both organisms and protein-rich oedema fluid within the alveolar spaces. This fungus is relatively common in the environment but rarely causes illness in healthy people. Immunocompromised individuals are at increased risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows granulomatous inflammation with caseous necrosis. \u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles virus\u003C/strong\u003E infection can show multinucleated giant cells (Warthin-Finkeldey cells). \u003Cstrong\u003EInfluenza A\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows diffuse alveolar damage with hyaline membranes. \u003Cstrong\u003ECytomegalovirus\u003C/strong\u003E pneumonia is characterised by enlarged cells with intranuclear inclusions (\u0027owl\u0027s eye\u0027 appearance).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia characteristically shows foamy or bubble-like alveolar exudates on histology","Pneumocystis pneumonia is an opportunistic infection commonly seen in immunocompromised patients"],"references":["Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Vaughn VM, Dickson RP, Horowitz JK, Flanders SA. 